F I G U R E 6 Regression decision and conditional inference tree analysis predicting corn grain yield. Split node parameter units are the same as those reported in Table 1, with $n$ representing the number of observations included in each split and terminal node for both approaches. Reported percentages in the terminal node of the regression decision tree reflect the percent of all observations binned in the respected node. Decision tree splits are determined by minimizing the residual sum of squares of the dataset, while conditional inference trees depend on an a priori significance level $(p<0.05)$ . Box plots for the conditional inference tree reflect the variability of yield $(\mathrm{Mg\thinspaceha}^{-1}$ ) at the terminal node with significant $p$ -values identified at each node split. Each box and whisker plot report the median (middle black line) with the middle $50\%$ of the data included within the box, and outliers identified by hollow points. POXC, permanganate oxidizable carbon;

 To prevent N losses during winter, applying N fertilizers to cereal crops in the autumn is generally prohibited, except for winter barley following other cereals. However, any N applied in the autumn reduced the amount that can be applied in the spring. This reduction could impact the profitability of winter barley cultivation, as the latest update of the German fertilizer ordinance (GER-FO, 2020) has been shown to restrict N fertilization to levels below economically optimal N rates for winter wheat (Kage et al., 2022). Thus, optimizing N use efficiency (NUE) is of crucial interest to maintain yield and protein while reaching environmental goals.  

Unlike wheat, there have been relatively few studies on the impact of different N fertilizer rates on winter barley yields. Maidl et al. (1996) tested ten different N treatments, varying both the amounts and timing of application. In general, N supply boosted grain yield, but the N level for maximum yield depended on the variety type (two- vs. six-row). Studies by Arisnabarreta and Miralles (2015); (2006) in Argentina, and Kennedy et al. (2017) in Ireland, suggest that yield improvements through breeding primarily resulted from a higher grain number per square meter, driven by better radiation interception. Hackett (2016) found similar N response curves across different winter barley types (line and hybrid types, two- and six-row types). Additionally, the impact of autumn N fertilization is still uncertain. Walker and Matthews (1991) and Maidl et al. (1996) observed enhanced tillering but found little to no yield improvements, leading them to recommend against autumn N application. In contrast, Sieling et al. (1998) reported that applying $80~\mathrm{kg}~\mathrm{N}~\mathrm{ha}^{-1}$ in the autumn did boost barley yield; however, the N use efficiency of the autumn-applied N remained low.  

