 Yet, research validating these theoretical frameworks or their related practices re­ mains in its infancy, particularly in K-12 classroom settings where MLLE are integrated with English speakers (Faltis & Valde´s, 2016; Goldenberg, 2013). Improving teacher effectiveness and classroom conditions for MLLE requires more intentional—and potentially radical—approaches to professional learning and practice.  

Several scholars have critically synthesized research on preparing content teachers for MLLE (e.g., Faltis and Vald´es, 2016; Viesca & Teemant, 2019). Viesca et al. (2019) identified three research strands: pedagogy, context, and orientations. The pedagogy studies present a complex picture, emphasizing a sociocultural focus on “inquiry, interaction, context, culture, discourse, and tangible and intangible resources” and highlight being “deeply active, connected, engaging for students, and relevant to their lives outside of school” (Viesca et al., 2019, p. 310). Domke and Cerrato’s (2024) review of 183 studies on various content-based instruction models found that high-frequency practices included using visuals, disciplinary language practices, small group instruction, and translanguaging related to language and content integration and content vocabulary translation. They concluded that teachers “lack training, time, and structures to support” (p. 25) effective integration of language and content.  

Viesca et al.’s (2019) context studies emphasized policy mandates. They argued for more “expanded, nuanced, centered, and complex investigations of context” that go beyond educational policy and include various local, disciplinary, cultural, and sociopo­ litical dimensions, which were rare in the reviewed research. According to Viesca et al. (2019), these studies concentrated on beliefs, attitudes, and ideologies concerning students, teacher learning, and practice, documenting deficit and assimilationist perspectives as prevalent among teachers (e.g., Mellom et al., 2018). Collaborative professional learning (e.g.,Martin-Beltra´n & Peercy, 2014; Mellom et al., 2018) and university coursework (e.g., Hansen-Thomas et al., 2016; Sharma & Lazar, 2014) were identified as beneficial in shifting teachers’ deficit ideologies (e.g., DelliCarpini & Alonso, 2014; Flores & Rosa, 2015;

